      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Clearing out everything over 6 months old, regardless of status, is a drastic measure that could potentially have unintended consequences. It's a bit like a \"garden of the damned\" approach, where you're clearing out everything that's not actively being used, without considering the potential value of the data that's still lurking in the shadows.\n\nIn many cases, data that's been around for 6 months or more can still be useful for analytics, business intelligence, or even just as a historical record. By clearing out everything that's older than 6 months, you may be inadvertently losing valuable insights or data that could be useful in the future.\n\nIt's worth considering a more nuanced approach, such as setting a \"time-to-live\" (TTL) for different types of data, so that you can control when and how data is purged. This would allow you to balance the need for space and performance with the need to retain valuable data.",
